truetext47954a0edbdc3300b53f341f7c9619f4falsefalsefalsefalsefalsec78ba79f2f62111004e4d3f62799b6ed0507239b2f62111004e4d3f62799b67eTable of Contents Shared Git Organization GitHub Authentication from ServiceNow Unclass-to-ProductionKB00101522022-09-21Using Git with ServiceNowkb_knowledgeerwinel_da2022-09-21 14:16:18global/ae2a5dc21bce9510ec0320efe54bcb557admin2022-10-31 18:28:480

Table of Contents

  • Shared Git Organization
  • GitHub Authentication from ServiceNow
  • Unclass-to-Production Synchronization
  • Legacy Development Repositories

Shared Git Organization

A shared Git organization has been created and can be accessed at the USASOC-HQ Git org website. Names of repositories for custom ServiceNow apps will begin with x_. Names of all other repositories should begin with something other than that.

Following is a list of some of the custom applications that are stored in git repositories:

  • x_g_inte_phys_net - Shared physical network definitions for pick lists, etc.
    • x_44813_phys_net_network - Legacy version of x_g_inte_phys_net which was deployed to our legacy production instance.
  • x_g_inte_usasoc_ia - USASOC Information Assurance app.
  • x_g_inte_off_net_s - Off-Net Software License Tracking app.
  • x_44813_usasoc_cst - General Legacy Customizations. To be superseded with a x_g_inte_* app once new production environment configuration has been determined.

GitHub Authentication from ServiceNow

You will need to set up a personal developer token which you will use in ServiceNow to authenticate to GitHub. Log into GitHub and open your personal access token list from the developer settings as depicted:

Under the "Select Scopes" section, Select the "repo" group, and then click the "Generate Token" button at the bottom.

Your personal access token will be presented in the next screen. From within ServiceNow, you will configure a basic credential using your GitHub login and the personal access token as the password.

In ServiceNow, you will create credentials as follows:

  1. Navigate to Connections and Credentials ⇛ Credentials.
  2. Click the "New" button and select "Basic Auth Credentials".
  3. In the "User name" field, enter your GitHub login name.
  4. In the "Password" field, enter the personal access token that was generated in GitHub.

Unclass-to-Production Synchronization

This procedure has not yet been fully tested and is subject to further adjustment.

  1. Create local bare clone of repository.
    Example: 
    $ git clone --bare --recursive https://github.com/USASOC-HQ/x_44813_phys_net_network
  2. Ensure target tag and branch has been fetched from the remote repository:
    1. List all tags to get the commit reference for the tag and to ensure the tag exists in the local repository. 
      $ git show-ref --tags
393bc8fca9bd180b57db4342d92c10c67316d113 refs/tags/V1.0.0.0
cafbf06e04c92145d814778a5366b58dd37ed9b2 refs/tags/V1.0.1.0​
    2. Ensure a local branch exists which contains the target tag. 
      $ git branch --contains 393bc8fca9bd180b57db4342d92c10c67316d113
origin/sn_instances/inscomscd
  3. Compress the contents of the entire repository folder into a ZIP file and copy it to the production network.
  4. On the production network extract the repository and create a new branch from the target version tag. See the Classified Network SDLC section of the SDLC page to determine the name of the new branch and for further instructions.

Legacy Development Repositories

Previously, all ServiceNow application git repositories were initiated from a personal developer instance and are attributed to a specific person (registration #44813), and not to this organization. Applications and their repositories whose names use the prefix x_44813_ should be re-created starting from the Cloud Dev Instance, as outlined in this SDLC, as time permits. ServiceNow applications that have been created on the Cloud Dev Instance will be prefixed with x_g_inte_.

No operational risk is incurred simply because an application was initiated through a personal dev instance. Such applications are just treated the same as any other 3rd party application. This also means that only the individual developer who owned that personal dev instance can make direct changes to that application without experiencing minor semantic complications. Another benefit of initiating apps from the cloud instance is that they are less prone to permissions and trust issues.

truetext47954a0edbdc3300b53f341f7c9619f4falsefalsefalsefalsefalsec78ba79f2f62111004e4d3f62799b6ed0507239b2f62111004e4d3f62799b67ePurpose To mitigate the risk of record number overlaps between 2 ServiceNow instances. ServiceNow instancesKB00101492022-09-20Migrating sequentially numbered records (i.e. KB articles) to another instancekb_knowledgeerwinel_da2022-09-20 15:45:19global/cfae5cf11b4a55101497a820f54bcbbe12admin2022-10-31 18:29:082Purpose

To mitigate the risk of record number overlaps between 2 ServiceNow instances.

ServiceNow instances track number sequencing for records independent of one another. When a sequentially-numbered record is created on one instance and then copied to another, there is a risk of the imported record having the same number as an existing record. This explains a way to manually ensure this does not happen.

An example use case would be when migrating a KB article from a ServiceNow instance on an unclassified network to an instance on a classified network that is not connected to the internet.

Assumptions / Pre-requisites

  • You have already created the record(s) that you wish to migrate.
  • You understand what, if any, related records that will need to be included with the target record.
  • You have administrative access on the source ServiceNow instance and are able to run a background script.
  • You have a basic understanding of exporting and importing records.
  • You are able to create new records on the target system.

Steps

In the following instructions, the term "Source instance" refers to the ServiceNow instance that contains the record you wish to export and "Target instance" refers to the ServiceNow instance you will be importing the record into.

  1. Reserve the next sequential number. Open up a new record form on the target instance, but do not modify any fields and do not save changes.
    • Make a note of the record number that was generated (i.e. KB0010514).
    • When the edit form is loaded, ServiceNow allocates the next sequential record number. If you don't save the new record, then that number will remain unused.
    Note: Make sure you are opening the actual new record edit form. For instance, if you are trying to create a new record from a service catalog link using a record producer, the sequential number may not be allocated as expected.
  2. Open the existing record on the source instance and copy the sys_id using the record menu.
  3.  Get table name. Make a note of the programmatic table name for the record type.
    • From the URL: If you can interpret web browser URLs, the programmatic name of the table may be part of the URL.
      For instance, in the following URL string portion, the table name is kb_knowledge:
      https://inscomscd.servicenowservices.com/nav_to.do?uri=%2Fkb_knowledge.do%3Fsys_id%3Dcfae5cf11b…
    • From Table Configuration: From the form menu, select Collection ⇒ Table. The programmatic name of the table will be in the "name" field.
  4. Change record number using a background script. Open a background script window and use the following template for the script to execute.
    var gr = new GlideRecord("table_name");
if (gr.get("sys_id")) {
    gr.number = "new_number";
    gr.update();
}
else
    gs.error("Record not found.");
    For instance, if you are changing the number of a KB article the script would look something similar to: 
    var gr = new GlideRecord("kb_knowledge");
if (gr.get("797ba49c6823481c80b3477ef8331741")) {
    gr.number = "KB0104231";
    gr.update();
}
else
    gs.error("Record not found.");
]]>General02100-01-01falsepublished#eef0ed700000trueimage/pngFormMenu.png6d643656f09d701b5cee4c9715393988d1a3576ba39990bc292214e20cab40052341591442414249availableerwinel_da2022-09-20 15:49:43b9ede8f11b4a55101497a820f54bcb333erwinel_da2022-09-20 15:49:43kb_knowledgecfae5cf11b4a55101497a820f54bcbbeH4sIAAAAAAAAAA==160b9ede8f11b4a55101497a820f54bcb33erwinel_da2022-09-20 15:49:_da2022-09-20 15:49:437dede8f11b4a55101497a820f54bcb33

truetext6816f79cc0a8016401c5a33be04be441falsefalsefalsefalsefalse0c78ba79f2f62111004e4d3f62799b6ed0507239b2f62111004e4d3f62799b67ePlugin Activation From the Activate Plugin option under the Instance Actions menu of the ServiceNow DeveloperKB0010154Personal Developer Instance Setupkb_knowledgeadmin2022-10-31 15:18:01global/15adabfe473a11103f08bce5536d434a14admin2022-10-31 19:48:520

Plugin Activation

  1. From the Activate Plugin option under the Instance Actions menu of the ServiceNow Developer website, activate the Software Asset Management Professional plugin.
  2. Navigate to All ⇒ System Definition ⇒ Plugins and activate the following:
    1. Agile Development
    2. Performance Analytics Premium for Project Portfolio Management
    3. Application Portfolio Management
  3. From the Plugin List, activate the following:
    1. Signature Pad (ID=com.snc.signaturepad)

GitHub Credentials

You will need to create a Credential record before you can import any applications from source control. To authenticate with GitHub you will need to create a personal access token.

Create Personal Access Token

  1. Log into GitHub.
  2. In the upper-right corner of any page, click your profile photo, then click Settings.
  3. In the left sidebar, click  Developer settings.
  4. In the left sidebar, under Personal access tokens, click Tokens (classic)
  5. Click Generate new token (classic).
  6. Optionally, under Note, add a note to describe the purpose of the token.
  7. Under Expiration, select an expiration for the token.
  8. Under Select scopes, select repo (Full control of private repositories).
  9. Click the Generate Token button.
  10. Save the personal access token that was generated. You will not be able to retrieve it again.

Create the initial Credential record

  1. In your Personal Developer Instance, use the All menu to open `Connections & Credentials` ⇒ `Credentials`.
  2. Click the New button.
  3. In the What type of Credentials would you like to create? list, select Basic Auth Credentials.
  4. Configure the Basic Auth Credentials record.
    • Name: A name to identify the Credential record.
    • Order: The order in which the credential is attempted if multiple credentials exist. The Order value is not used for source control.
    • User name: The username to authenticate to the source control repository.
    • Password: Use a personal access token instead of a password.
    • Active: Select to make the credential available for use.
    • Credential alias: A list of integrations that use the credential. The Credential alias is not used for source control.
  5. Click the Submit button.

More Information

  • GitHub Guide
  • Creating a personal access token
  • Managing the Development Environment

truetext6816f79cc0a8016401c5a33be04be441falsefalsefalsefalsefalse0c78ba79f2f62111004e4d3f62799b6ed0507239b2f62111004e4d3f62799b67eTable of Contents Lifecycle Stages Overview Development Cloud Development On-Premises Introduction /KB00101512022-10-20ServiceNow SDLCkb_knowledgeadmin2022-10-20 18:35:55global/0b3d23132fa2111004e4d3f62799b6787admin2022-10-31 18:28:560

Table of Contents

  • Lifecycle Stages Overview
    • Development
      • Cloud Development
      • On-Premises Introduction / Development
    • User Acceptance Testing
    • Production
  • Sandbox Instances
  • ServiceNow Instance Names

Lifecycle Stages Overview

A modified SDLC is required because on-premises instances are not accessible from the internet. When new functionality and changes are initiated on a cloud instance, it will allow for more effective support from product vendors when support is required.

Development

Cloud Development

The Shared Cloud Instance and Personal Developer Instances will be used during the Development stage.

Changes to existing scopes should be made within a personal developer instance, when available. Changes can then be pushed to the shared cloud instance.

New scoped applications should be created in the shared cloud instance so it has the correct scope name prefix.

On-Premises Introduction / Development

Changes are exported from the shared cloud instance and imported into the On-premises Development Instance, after which any modifications or configuration that could not be implemented on the internet-facing instance are applied.

Any applicable integration testing is also conducted on the on-prem development instance.

User Acceptance Testing

Changes are applied to the On-premises Test Instance and validated by the product owner and users that were assigned to conduct tests.

This also serves to validate any post-deployment configuration that needs to be implemented.

Production

After user acceptance testing has passed, changes are applied to the Production Instance.

Sandbox Instances

There are instances on the stand-alone Dev/Test network which represent each of the instances on the production network. These are use for testing system-wide changes, such as platform upgrades and testing backup and restore tasks.

ServiceNow Instance Names

Shared Cloud Instance
Shared internet-facing Development instance on ServiceNow's Gov Cloud.
Personal Developer Instance
Personal internet-facing instances provided by ServiceNow for unclassified development. Typically changes are pushed to a Git repository and then pulled into the Shared Cloud Instance.
On-premises Development Instance
Development instance that is accessible only from the production network.
On-premises Test Instance
User Acceptance Testing instance that is accessible only from the production network.
Production Instance
The Production ServiceNow instance which is not accessible from the internet.
Sandbox Dev Instance
Sandbox instance on the stand-alone dev/test network for testing activities which affect the On-premises Development Instance.
Sandbox Test Instance
Sandbox instance on the stand-alone dev/test network for testing activities which affect the On-premises Test Instance.
Sandbox Production Instance
Sandbox instance on the stand-alone dev/test network for testing activities which affect the Production Instance.
]]>General02100-01-01truepublished
